narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Not much tbh. Did not love this class even though I did it in high school basically

I gained a great foundation in the subject of Calculus, and I was also able to learn how to properly study for college math so as to ensure that I am not only understanding the concepts, but also able to apply them properly.

I developed a better sense on how to think rationally using presented information and mathematical concepts. This course also emphasized collaboration, so there was a strong learning curve on how to work with my peers on p sets and in study groups to maximize our efforts in the class. The overall content was similar to AP Calculus BC with a stronger emphasis on conceptual knowledge.
I learned a lot about many topics in Calculus II, common techniques related to them, and how to identify them in math problems.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: My TF who was teaching the class was a super nice person but had 0 teaching experience while some classes were taught by professors and they definitely learned the material better than I did which I think is semi-unfair. So if your taking this make sure you have the professor.

The strengths are that several resources were provided for me to learn the material further and my instructor was thorough in his explanations. Some weaknesses are that sometimes I felt uncomfortable to ask a question in class and some of the homework assignments did not align with the examinations.

I dont know that I found the explorations incredibly helpful- they helped to provide some sense of what I was going to be covering in class, but they didnt do the most in solidifying or furthering my understanding.
I didnt feel like concepts were explained with any sort of reasoning, rather they were simply given to  us and we were told this works. So none of us knew why something worked.

Strengths of the course include how the course is well organized, there is a very strong support system, the rate that content is introduced is very manageable, and how the problems selected for problem sets are well chosen and non-repetitive. Weaknesses include how there is a bit of variation between the quality of instructors in the courses in terms of teaching style and the information given and how the final exam is weighed very highly in the final grade.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yeah if you want to learn calc
I would recommend this course because it is designed to help an incoming student learn Calculus with resources to guide them along.

Yes, if this course was required for their major or they needed to take a math credit. While not the most interesting material, this course provides a solid foundation for material that one will cover in other courses, especially STEM majors.
No, because I felt like I struggled with the confusing explanations given in class.

I would recommend this course to another student as it intuitively builds on top of Calculus I concepts, without requiring you to remember absolutely everything. The exam problems' difficulty is very fair compared to the difficulty of the problem sets and the content covered in class. The explorations let you intuitively understand the concepts.
